eristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Gwilym","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwilim","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"Goch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Italian <b>Rocco</b>; ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilym Goch ap Ieuan was born about 1344, in Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Gwilym \" Goch\" ap Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1344–":"umbes 1344–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1365–1438":"1365–1438","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1344–Female":"1344–Surnud","ABT    1374":"umbes 1374","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","about 1344":"umbes 1344","1438":"1438","Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Pen-pont,Llansbyddyd,Breconshire,Wales":"Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1344–":"noin 1344–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1365–1438":"1365–1438","1374–Male":"1374–Kuollut","1344–Female":"1344–Kuollut","ABT    1374":"noin 1374","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","about 1344":"noin 1344","1438":"1438","Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Pen-pont,Llansbyddyd,Breconshire,Wales":"Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1344–":"environ 1344–Décédée","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1365–1438":"1365–1438","1374–Male":"1374–Décédé","1344–Female":"1344–Décédée","ABT    1374":"environ 1374","1344":"1344","1365":"1365","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","about 1344":"environ 1344","1438":"1438","Penpont, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Penpont, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","of Pen-pont,Llansbyddyd,Breconshire,Wales":"Penpont, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilym Goch ap Ieuan est née environ 1344, à Penpont, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec Gwilym \" Goch\" ap Ieuan."},"de":{"about 1344–":"um 1344–Versto